cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use neuropulse in academic work, please cite as below."
type: software
title: "neuropulse: a real-time 1:1 visualization of a full-scale LLM forward pass in the browser"
authors:
  - family-names: Günaydın
    given-names: Ahmet Barış
    email: hi@barisgunaydin.com
    affiliation: Independent researcher
# doi: 10.5281/zenodo.XXXXXXXX   # add after the GitHub release mints it
repository-code: "https://github.com/abgnydn/neuropulse"
url: "https://neuropulse.live"
license: MIT
version: 0.2.0
date-released: 2026-06-02
keywords:
  - WebGPU
  - WGSL
  - large language models
  - transformer
  - Phi-3
  - mechanistic interpretability
  - visualization
  - in-browser computation
  - reproducible research
  - pre-registration
abstract: >-
  neuropulse renders a real forward pass of Phi-3-mini-4k-instruct in a web
  browser, 1:1 from live WebGPU activations — no server, no sampling, no
  approximation. The engine is a hand-written Phi-3 decode loop built from
  eleven WGSL compute kernels over MLC q4f16_1 weights; each generated token is
  292 GPU dispatches headless (348 with the visualizer reading back per-layer
  attention scores and eight logit-lens probes). Every intermediate tensor is
  read back and drawn on a Three.js scene so a 3.8B-parameter transformer can
  be watched as it runs. The project is an empirical lab: a precision/methods
  note, a pinned HuggingFace cross-validation artifact with per-layer L2/cosine
  bounds, and a pre-registered ablation log of dated, falsifiable claims.
  Experiment E45 tests and falsifies the zero-shot-inference variant of a
  continuous-attention self-consistency fixed point. The Butterfly
  context-compaction study that ran on this platform lives in its own
  repository (github.com/abgnydn/butterfly).
